crowdsourced_yara_results.description: This signature detects an Adobe Type 1 Font. The Type 1 Font Format is a standardized font format for digital imaging applications.
crowdsourced_yara_results.author: InQuest Labs

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis:
While a technical analysis of the PDF's internal structure found no automatic execution triggers, embedded scripts, or other direct threats, the document's visual layer is unequivocally malicious. The content is a social engineering lure designed to deceive the recipient. It impersonates trusted brands, including Adobe and Commerce Bank, to present a fake security update notification that blocks the underlying content.

The document's primary purpose is to convince the user that they must download and manually execute an external file to view the purported bank statement. It provides a clear call-to-action button and explicit instructions to run the downloaded file. This tactic is a classic method for tricking users into installing malware. The presence of grammatical errors further undermines the document's legitimacy. Although the PDF itself is passive and contains no executable code, it functions as the delivery vehicle for a malicious payload.
